Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.895 --> 00:00:03.520
MALE SPEAKER: Good
afternoon, everyone.

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:06.560
Welcome to another outstanding
Talks at Google Speech.

00:00:06.560 --> 00:00:09.510
We are thrilled and honored to
have Chef Daniel Boulud here

00:00:09.510 --> 00:00:11.630
today from New York.

00:00:11.630 --> 00:00:14.270
From his time at Le
Cirque to his current work

00:00:14.270 --> 00:00:17.060
with the Bocuse d'Or team,
and his entire portfolio

00:00:17.060 --> 00:00:19.630
of restaurants,
Daniel has really

00:00:19.630 --> 00:00:22.270
been advancing French cuisine
and also incorporating

00:00:22.270 --> 00:00:26.419
American tastes and
ingredients into the mix.

00:00:26.419 --> 00:00:27.960
And so he's here
today speaking to us

00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:31.700
about his new book called
"Daniel: My French Cuisine."

00:00:31.700 --> 00:00:35.780
And it chronicles about
75 of his favorite dishes,

00:00:35.780 --> 00:00:38.850
some from the restaurants,
some from France itself.

00:00:38.850 --> 00:00:41.770
And so he'll be talking to
us about that in more detail

00:00:41.770 --> 00:00:42.480
today.

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:44.810
And we do have a microphone
at the end for questions.

00:00:44.810 --> 00:00:46.810
So please join me in
welcoming Daniel to Google.

00:00:46.810 --> 00:00:47.626
Thanks.

00:00:47.626 --> 00:00:49.084
DANIEL BOULUD:
Thank you very much.

00:00:49.084 --> 00:00:49.583
Thank you.

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:55.210
I got the mic.

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:56.810
Good afternoon, everybody.

00:00:56.810 --> 00:01:02.400
So how many of you
are good cooks?

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:02.900
Pas mal.

00:01:02.900 --> 00:01:05.334
Good chefs?

00:01:05.334 --> 00:01:07.000
There are a few.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:08.410
But, no, thank you.

00:01:08.410 --> 00:01:10.800
I had a wonderful
lunch here, by the way.

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:15.660
And it seems like you are
the luckiest people on earth.

00:01:15.660 --> 00:01:20.380
Not only you are in California
but you have amazing chef also.

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:23.410
I tasted your
pumpkin soup in one

00:01:23.410 --> 00:01:31.590
and then I finished my lunch
with-- which cafeteria was it?

00:01:31.590 --> 00:01:33.130
Which restaurant?

00:01:33.130 --> 00:01:34.120
Hangout, yeah.

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:35.320
Exactly.

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:37.470
So, fantastic.

00:01:37.470 --> 00:01:41.310
Well cooking, it's,
of course, something

00:01:41.310 --> 00:01:44.330
you learn early, often.

00:01:44.330 --> 00:01:47.620
I learned it at 14,
but I knew that I

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:51.290
wanted to be a cook when
I was about 10 to 12.

00:01:51.290 --> 00:01:53.050
I was born and
raised on the farm,

00:01:53.050 --> 00:01:58.640
and today every chef
dreams to be farmer chef.

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:00.850
It's farm to table.

00:02:00.850 --> 00:02:05.440
It's directly garden to
table as close as possible.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:08.539
And we have seen
models of that growing

00:02:08.539 --> 00:02:11.420
and I think it's fantastic.

00:02:11.420 --> 00:02:13.220
I don't have my
farm yet, but I do

00:02:13.220 --> 00:02:15.830
remember the one I
had in France where

00:02:15.830 --> 00:02:19.120
we grew everything, all
kinds of vegetables.

00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:22.380
We also had livestock.

00:02:22.380 --> 00:02:26.950
Cows, and goats-- 40 goats--
and making goat cheese.

00:02:26.950 --> 00:02:31.190
Pigs, and rabbit, and
turkey, and geese,

00:02:31.190 --> 00:02:35.610
and squab, and
chicken, and duck.

00:02:35.610 --> 00:02:37.740
And every week we would
go to the farmer's market

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:42.820
and bring all the harvest
we had that particular week.

00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:49.330
And it's true, certainly,
about how humble

00:02:49.330 --> 00:02:53.290
and how important it is
about life, ingredient.

00:02:53.290 --> 00:02:54.900
And when you're a
chef I think it's

00:02:54.900 --> 00:02:57.440
the most important
thing you hang on

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:01.050
and the most important
thing you fight for.

00:03:01.050 --> 00:03:02.800
And, certainly, the
most important things,

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:07.710
we need almost a trust
to have access to.

00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:15.760
Growing up on the farm,
when I wanted to be a cook,

00:03:15.760 --> 00:03:17.990
my parents and
some friends helped

00:03:17.990 --> 00:03:20.650
me to get in one of the
best restaurants in Lyon.

00:03:20.650 --> 00:03:25.420
So I started in Lyon at
14, and 2 star restaurant.

00:03:25.420 --> 00:03:26.220
Fantastic.

00:03:26.220 --> 00:03:31.510
And Lyon is kind of the
mecca of chefs in France.

00:03:31.510 --> 00:03:34.470
I right away knew
that I was entering

00:03:34.470 --> 00:03:40.340
a very, very special club,
a very spatial society,

00:03:40.340 --> 00:03:45.930
a real community of people
who share the same passion

00:03:45.930 --> 00:03:47.770
and have the same ambition.

00:03:47.770 --> 00:03:51.700
But yet, it was at the
local level of Lyon,

00:03:51.700 --> 00:03:54.640
except for one man,
Paul Bocuse, who

00:03:54.640 --> 00:03:57.860
was the chef who was
starting to travel the world

00:03:57.860 --> 00:04:01.790
and taking the cuisine of
Lyon to Rio de Janeiro,

00:04:01.790 --> 00:04:07.580
to Tokyo, to
California at Mondavi.

00:04:07.580 --> 00:04:09.770
Robert Mondavi was
the first one who

00:04:09.770 --> 00:04:12.680
brought French
chefs to California

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:15.710
and were make them cook
and do demonstrations

00:04:15.710 --> 00:04:17.089
there in Napa Valley.

00:04:19.779 --> 00:04:23.850
So now in the early '70s, really
French cuisine is changing.

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:26.270
And I'm this young
chef, so I decided

00:04:26.270 --> 00:04:29.130
to work for some of the
best chefs in France.

00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:31.560
For me it was very
important to choose someone

00:04:31.560 --> 00:04:36.280
who had the same
fundamentals as the one

00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:40.380
I started to work with and also
someone who had three Michelin

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:46.020
stars, because I felt that I had
a start at a two Michelin star

00:04:46.020 --> 00:04:50.650
and I wanted to know more
about the three Michelin star

00:04:50.650 --> 00:04:51.150
restaurant.

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:56.200
But I felt strong with
the two star background

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:59.090
because I learned a
lot during that time.

00:04:59.090 --> 00:05:01.450
And so I went and I did
my tour de France, what

00:05:01.450 --> 00:05:05.220
we call the tour de France,
where you have to-- I

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:08.240
wanted to work in the south,
so I went to Provence,

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:10.730
and I went to Moulin
de Mougins in Cannes.

00:05:10.730 --> 00:05:12.280
It just had three
stars that year.

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:14.350
It was very exhilarating.

00:05:14.350 --> 00:05:18.370
I mean the energy, the talent
who is gathering around you

00:05:18.370 --> 00:05:20.360
because, of course, he
received so many resumes

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:22.200
that he can be a
little selective.

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:24.890
And then after I moved to
the southwest of France

00:05:24.890 --> 00:05:28.450
to Michel Guerard, I moved
to Burgundy in the Rhone,

00:05:28.450 --> 00:05:32.610
in Burgundy region
with Georges Blanc.

00:05:32.610 --> 00:05:33.750
And then I left France.

00:05:33.750 --> 00:05:34.720
I went to Denmark.

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:38.050
And in '80 I came
to America because I

00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:39.110
wanted to be like them.

00:05:39.110 --> 00:05:41.180
I wanted to travel.

00:05:41.180 --> 00:05:43.760
They seem to have the good
time when they travel.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:45.890
And they also seem
to bring ideas.

00:05:45.890 --> 00:05:50.450
And all the traveling those
chefs in the '70s were doing

00:05:50.450 --> 00:05:53.220
were really also-- not
only they were bringing

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:55.950
their food and their
culture to a country,

00:05:55.950 --> 00:05:58.260
but they were also
bringing ideas.

00:05:58.260 --> 00:06:01.560
And I always love--
I wouldn't have

00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:06.420
been a chef if I didn't want to
travel and be able to discover

00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:09.920
where else can we cook and
what else there is out there.

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:13.750
And so came to Washington, DC.

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:17.020
I did two years in
DC as a private chef

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:19.690
in a residence
for an ambassador.

00:06:19.690 --> 00:06:23.820
And that was kind of a very
cushy job, not too fascinating.

00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:27.180
But I had a chance to really
go to the market every day

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:29.490
there in DC, having
small suppliers.

00:06:29.490 --> 00:06:32.700
Because I was not cooking
for a large amount of people

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:34.550
I was depending on
small suppliers.

00:06:34.550 --> 00:06:36.190
And that was already
the beginning

00:06:36.190 --> 00:06:40.180
of having local farmers
there and local suppliers.

00:06:40.180 --> 00:06:41.920
And there was a great
chef there also,

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:44.900
Jean-Louis Palladin, who had
a restaurant at the Watergate,

00:06:44.900 --> 00:06:46.550
in the basement
of the Watergate.

00:06:46.550 --> 00:06:48.840
And he had any other
ingredient I couldn't find,

00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:49.820
he had it there.

00:06:49.820 --> 00:06:52.190
So he was great.

00:06:52.190 --> 00:06:54.990
Then after DC I
felt like New York

00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:57.970
has to be my stop before
I go back to France.

00:06:57.970 --> 00:07:00.820
And I made a stop in
New York and never left.

00:07:00.820 --> 00:07:03.490
And so from that
I had the chance

00:07:03.490 --> 00:07:06.550
to work in a great restaurant
called Le Cirque when

00:07:06.550 --> 00:07:09.340
the restaurant was in
transition of being famous

00:07:09.340 --> 00:07:14.110
for maybe more its clientele
dining there than the food,

00:07:14.110 --> 00:07:20.430
and being famous-- because it
was famous-- but for its owner

00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:23.870
Sirio Maccioni, an
Italian restaurateur.

00:07:23.870 --> 00:07:26.510
Incredible professional.

00:07:26.510 --> 00:07:35.090
But in the kitchen there was a
big gap of direction and focus.

00:07:35.090 --> 00:07:37.900
And so I worked there six years.

00:07:37.900 --> 00:07:39.820
And that helped
me prove the world

00:07:39.820 --> 00:07:42.110
that I could maybe
raise enough money

00:07:42.110 --> 00:07:44.040
to open my own restaurant.

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:47.580
And 20 years ago
I opened Daniel.

00:07:47.580 --> 00:07:56.280
And so this book is-- but
it's about the evolution

00:07:56.280 --> 00:07:59.860
and the growth of the last
20 years as well for me.

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:01.950
And I think we see
also the evolution

00:08:01.950 --> 00:08:04.140
at the gross in America.

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:06.890
When I arrived in
New York and I was

00:08:06.890 --> 00:08:10.450
my own executive
sous-chef-- executive

00:08:10.450 --> 00:08:14.600
sous-chef job-- Thomas
Keller was my chef de partie

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:16.780
in the poisson.

00:08:16.780 --> 00:08:18.880
Alfred Portale was
chef garde manger,

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:22.090
which is from Gotham Bar
and Grill in New York.

00:08:22.090 --> 00:08:24.500
Billy Yosses, the pastry
chef of the White House

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:27.060
was my garde manger as well.

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:29.970
And we had all kinds of
rock stars of the moment.

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:31.510
We were just young cooks.

00:08:31.510 --> 00:08:36.950
And that was before Thomas
went to France and all that.

00:08:36.950 --> 00:08:40.150
And they were like-- every
day we were witnessing

00:08:40.150 --> 00:08:43.100
talent coming in,
talent growing in.

00:08:43.100 --> 00:08:46.690
And I went to the Plaza in the
after, and even at Le Cirque

00:08:46.690 --> 00:08:49.200
I have so many
alumni, whereas today

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:51.980
are very influential chefs
all over the country.

00:08:51.980 --> 00:08:55.270
But those alumni have already
produced a new generation

00:08:55.270 --> 00:08:57.610
of chefs, and we
see them coming now.

00:08:57.610 --> 00:09:01.580
And I think that's the exciting
part, is then, of course,

00:09:01.580 --> 00:09:04.660
they learn with
great chefs like me

00:09:04.660 --> 00:09:09.650
and they understand
tradition, and they

00:09:09.650 --> 00:09:11.810
try to create an
evolution with that

00:09:11.810 --> 00:09:14.630
and try to be really
relevant to their time.

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:17.830
And I think, for me, that's
what I've tried to always do,

00:09:17.830 --> 00:09:20.790
but yet I'm still very French.

00:09:20.790 --> 00:09:24.320
I am being in
America for 30 years,

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:26.870
you can't take the
French out of me still.

00:09:26.870 --> 00:09:29.370
And it's OK.

00:09:29.370 --> 00:09:32.630
When it comes to
cooking, it's acceptable.

00:09:32.630 --> 00:09:37.269
For other things, I don't
know if it's all acceptable,

00:09:37.269 --> 00:09:39.310
especially with the
politician we have right now.

00:09:42.680 --> 00:09:45.830
But it's about ambition.

00:09:45.830 --> 00:09:49.620
And I think chefs, it
takes a lot of ambition

00:09:49.620 --> 00:09:51.570
to become a great chef.

00:09:51.570 --> 00:09:54.140
But it takes a
lot of discipline,

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:59.030
it takes a lot of hard work,
it takes a lot of sacrifice.

00:09:59.030 --> 00:10:03.000
It takes lot of
motivation as well.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:09.770
And I think we can all
share our own story

00:10:09.770 --> 00:10:12.070
about how to become a chef.

00:10:12.070 --> 00:10:15.270
I actually I wrote a book
called "Letter to a Young Chef"

00:10:15.270 --> 00:10:22.600
and it's about what it
took for me as a young chef

00:10:22.600 --> 00:10:25.580
to become who I am, but
also what it will take

00:10:25.580 --> 00:10:28.910
you, the young chef,
to eventually succeed,

00:10:28.910 --> 00:10:30.760
even if we're in
a different time.

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:33.220
I think it's a
timeless lesson, I

00:10:33.220 --> 00:10:35.290
think, for what I wrote there.

00:10:35.290 --> 00:10:37.950
And it's still a lot
of use by students

00:10:37.950 --> 00:10:41.510
at cooking schools for
being inspired, being

00:10:41.510 --> 00:10:45.130
driven, and staying
on the course,

00:10:45.130 --> 00:10:49.290
and-- having chosen
that profession--

00:10:49.290 --> 00:10:52.530
to make a difference in
the future with themselves

00:10:52.530 --> 00:10:56.040
and with their teams.

00:10:56.040 --> 00:10:56.690
So the book.

00:10:59.680 --> 00:11:03.230
And one word also
is to, of course,

00:11:03.230 --> 00:11:05.367
for every one I worked
and for everything I

00:11:05.367 --> 00:11:08.740
expect from my staff, is to
always exceed expectations.

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:11.630
And I think that's
something where,

00:11:11.630 --> 00:11:15.460
at a certain level
of perfection you

00:11:15.460 --> 00:11:19.000
have to have everyone
exceed expectations.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.710
And that's the only way
those young chefs will

00:11:21.710 --> 00:11:27.220
grow to become the leaders,
the ones who can definitely

00:11:27.220 --> 00:11:29.370
prove that.

00:11:29.370 --> 00:11:36.160
So the book is about Daniel
today, the restaurant.

00:11:36.160 --> 00:11:39.720
It's not the whole story
about the last 20 years.

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:42.820
I wrote seven other
books and they

00:11:42.820 --> 00:11:45.790
were all telling
different story,

00:11:45.790 --> 00:11:48.920
but also sometimes geared
more for home cooking,

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:51.680
being more comfortable
with the idea of that.

00:11:51.680 --> 00:11:54.550
And this one was
more about capturing

00:11:54.550 --> 00:11:57.910
what the restaurant
represents today.

00:11:57.910 --> 00:12:00.730
Many people know
Daniel the restaurant?

00:12:00.730 --> 00:12:02.612
Yes, you have been there?

00:12:02.612 --> 00:12:04.070
Mhmm.

00:12:04.070 --> 00:12:09.990
So I think it's one of
those restaurants-- it's

00:12:09.990 --> 00:12:11.140
a grand restaurant.

00:12:11.140 --> 00:12:14.820
And there is not too many
in America left like that.

00:12:14.820 --> 00:12:21.180
And I feel that it's a landmark
in New York now after 20 years.

00:12:21.180 --> 00:12:23.470
It's not the landmark,
but it will be one day.

00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:28.840
But at least the restaurant
has sort of an era of the past

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:32.000
and a feel of the present.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:37.060
And I think that's a little bit
also what I do in my cooking.

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:44.804
It's about tradition and
it's about evolution as well.

00:12:44.804 --> 00:12:45.470
So I don't know.

00:12:45.470 --> 00:12:49.270
Do you have couple of
pictures we can do?

00:12:49.270 --> 00:12:52.250
Yeah, let's do a little
video introduction.

00:12:52.250 --> 00:12:56.590
But otherwise is there
any other subjects

00:12:56.590 --> 00:12:59.080
you would like me
to approach for you

00:12:59.080 --> 00:13:02.820
while I am here,
before the video?

00:13:02.820 --> 00:13:03.907
Yes, tell me.

00:13:03.907 --> 00:13:05.990
AUDIENCE: There was an
article a couple months ago

00:13:05.990 --> 00:13:07.370
in "Vanity Fair"
that was talking

00:13:07.370 --> 00:13:11.080
about the generation of
chefs that you mentioned

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:14.920
and the idea of tasting menus
versus a la carte ordering

00:13:14.920 --> 00:13:18.870
options, and how a lot of it
was the tasting menus just sort

00:13:18.870 --> 00:13:21.964
of give the chef ultimate
authority, make things easier,

00:13:21.964 --> 00:13:24.130
predict how much food you're
going to need to order,

00:13:24.130 --> 00:13:25.900
different ingredients,
and so forth.

00:13:25.900 --> 00:13:28.200
But then they were sort
of saying that also it

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:31.480
kind of lost sight of
the patron as being

00:13:31.480 --> 00:13:34.499
like the ultimate boss in
terms of what they want to eat.

00:13:34.499 --> 00:13:36.290
So I was just kind of
curious your thoughts

00:13:36.290 --> 00:13:39.764
on how that works
and do you think

00:13:39.764 --> 00:13:40.930
one's better than the other?

00:13:40.930 --> 00:13:41.714
Your philosophy.

00:13:41.714 --> 00:13:43.130
DANIEL BOULUD: I
think no, no, no.

00:13:43.130 --> 00:13:46.030
The tasting menu
and post tasting

00:13:46.030 --> 00:13:51.410
menu work very well if you
have 20, 30, 50 seats, maybe.

00:13:51.410 --> 00:13:58.390
And your goal is to try to
not worry about any clientele

00:13:58.390 --> 00:14:00.920
locally, any
clientele nationally,

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:07.110
you just want to
really show them

00:14:07.110 --> 00:14:10.530
the restaurant cooks this
way and no other way.

00:14:10.530 --> 00:14:11.480
I think it's nice.

00:14:11.480 --> 00:14:16.380
For me, this is not what I do.

00:14:16.380 --> 00:14:20.080
I like to create a menu
where there is choice.

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:23.950
I can do 10, 12, 14 course
after with the menu,

00:14:23.950 --> 00:14:26.280
but I like to offer
options to the customer

