or partridge and you

00:30:31.500 --> 00:30:33.950
have pieces of
lard on the bottom,

00:30:33.950 --> 00:30:35.640
and you can put some
potatoes, and then

00:30:35.640 --> 00:30:37.610
you have the braised
cabbage, and then

00:30:37.610 --> 00:30:39.200
you put the whole
pheasant which has

00:30:39.200 --> 00:30:41.310
been pre-roasted and
flambe with cognac.

00:30:41.310 --> 00:30:44.130
And then you cover
it with cabbage

00:30:44.130 --> 00:30:46.580
and then you bake it in
the oven like that too.

00:30:46.580 --> 00:30:49.980
So the game birds
release all its flavor.

00:30:49.980 --> 00:30:51.890
And so here I wanted
to make a chartreuse

00:30:51.890 --> 00:30:53.260
like you have never seen.

00:30:53.260 --> 00:30:55.330
So first we have a
young chef, Chad,

00:30:55.330 --> 00:30:57.200
who has worked on
the book there.

00:30:57.200 --> 00:31:03.130
And he's becoming mathematician
at Columbia, but he was a chef.

00:31:03.130 --> 00:31:05.880
He went back to Columbia
to be a mathematician.

00:31:05.880 --> 00:31:08.340
So I made him calculate
all the carrot, turnips,

00:31:08.340 --> 00:31:10.850
and yellow carrot,
and orange carrot too.

00:31:10.850 --> 00:31:13.340
I have the perfect
field of the mold.

00:31:13.340 --> 00:31:15.260
And then after we line
it up with cabbage

00:31:15.260 --> 00:31:18.590
leaves, and then we fill it
up with the braised cabbage.

00:31:18.590 --> 00:31:22.350
And then this is a
slice of woodcock.

00:31:22.350 --> 00:31:27.360
Woodcock, add those birds'
heads on top of that.

00:31:27.360 --> 00:31:35.270
And so we add first a
cabbage molded with the lard,

00:31:35.270 --> 00:31:39.410
with the bacon, and this is
filled with crushed potato,

00:31:39.410 --> 00:31:41.970
with foie gras fat,
and then slice of foie

00:31:41.970 --> 00:31:45.560
gras, and dove--
little bird dove.

00:31:45.560 --> 00:31:47.410
So those are all
wild birds in a way.

00:31:47.410 --> 00:31:52.620
And then inside is partridge,
woodcock, and pheasant.

00:31:52.620 --> 00:31:54.340
Three types of birds.

00:31:54.340 --> 00:31:57.870
And then we take the innards
of the partridge, pheasant,

00:31:57.870 --> 00:32:01.420
and decasse and we make a
little stuffed cabbage on top.

00:32:01.420 --> 00:32:07.990
And so that's a little sauvage,
but I have wonderful hunters

00:32:07.990 --> 00:32:09.750
in New York, friends hunters.

00:32:09.750 --> 00:32:13.720
And so they bring
me birds to New York

00:32:13.720 --> 00:32:17.810
to play with that
when I want to.

00:32:17.810 --> 00:32:19.220
And this is duck a la presse.

00:32:19.220 --> 00:32:23.650
So this gentlemen here
has been my best customer

00:32:23.650 --> 00:32:26.810
since I opened the restaurant.

00:32:26.810 --> 00:32:29.940
For 20 years, every week,
he eats in the restaurant.

00:32:29.940 --> 00:32:31.680
And now he's a retired lawyer.

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:33.830
And so now he works in
the kitchen as well.

00:32:33.830 --> 00:32:36.570
During the morning he comes
and spends time with the chef

00:32:36.570 --> 00:32:40.630
and then he go home, he
change and come for dinner.

00:32:40.630 --> 00:32:44.260
And there's a whole story about
the duck press in the book

00:32:44.260 --> 00:32:49.960
and how this duck press
was put back to life.

00:32:49.960 --> 00:32:53.380
And with the recipe as well,
will belong to somebody

00:32:53.380 --> 00:32:57.920
in the '30s in America who
was a lawyer from Cleveland,

00:32:57.920 --> 00:33:00.050
who was going to the
21 Club all the time

00:33:00.050 --> 00:33:01.969
and took a duck press
home and started

00:33:01.969 --> 00:33:03.760
to make all kinds of
recipes for his friend

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:06.970
because he was also a hunter.

00:33:06.970 --> 00:33:12.330
And so I revived the recipe
and revived the duck press

00:33:12.330 --> 00:33:13.560
50 years later.

00:33:13.560 --> 00:33:17.060
And we have created
a canard au sang

00:33:17.060 --> 00:33:20.710
which is a classic
French recipe as well.

00:33:20.710 --> 00:33:24.500
So after the session
of iconic-- which

00:33:24.500 --> 00:33:28.670
there is more in the book, many
more, and very interesting text

00:33:28.670 --> 00:33:30.480
will really touch
every chef-- then

00:33:30.480 --> 00:33:32.800
we have also the home section.

00:33:32.800 --> 00:33:37.460
I live right above Daniel
and so that's convenient

00:33:37.460 --> 00:33:44.250
because I'm always at work
and I am easily at home.

00:33:44.250 --> 00:33:49.200
So I wanted to do home
recipe who was also

00:33:49.200 --> 00:33:51.410
approachable to people
who buy this book

00:33:51.410 --> 00:33:53.940
but feel that all the other
recipes, it's a little bit

00:33:53.940 --> 00:33:55.220
overwhelming.

00:33:55.220 --> 00:33:59.230
And so this, I chose
different region of France

00:33:59.230 --> 00:34:02.280
for that because I felt the
book is my French cuisine

00:34:02.280 --> 00:34:06.560
and often when I cook at home
I think of regional France.

00:34:06.560 --> 00:34:09.620
So this is about Alsace,
Normandy, Provence,

00:34:09.620 --> 00:34:11.409
and Lyon, my hometown.

00:34:11.409 --> 00:34:12.800
So picture as a little mix.

00:34:12.800 --> 00:34:15.370
And Catherine, my wife,
is there-- thank you.

00:34:15.370 --> 00:34:19.239
She is my partner in
the kitchen upstairs.

00:34:19.239 --> 00:34:25.409
So that's the more
approachable Daniel in a way.

00:34:25.409 --> 00:34:26.330
But very expensive.

00:34:26.330 --> 00:34:29.770
If you want to eat in my home it
will cost you more than double.

00:34:29.770 --> 00:34:34.330
Actually I opened my home for
dinner but only for charity.

00:34:34.330 --> 00:34:37.429
I'm the co-president
of Citymeals-On-Wheels.

00:34:37.429 --> 00:34:41.489
And for Citymeals I sell dinner
at home for usually eight

00:34:41.489 --> 00:34:45.330
people, and it sells
for $30-$40,000.

00:34:45.330 --> 00:34:48.750
So it's always a good use
of my kitchen that day,

00:34:48.750 --> 00:34:51.980
for a good purpose.

00:34:51.980 --> 00:34:55.880
But any questions about
French cuisine, anyone?

00:34:55.880 --> 00:34:57.080
Yes?

00:34:57.080 --> 00:34:59.621
AUDIENCE: I have to say I'm very
interested in French cuisine

00:34:59.621 --> 00:35:01.460
and equally interested
in French wine.

00:35:01.460 --> 00:35:04.000
I have a trouble though when
I go to a fancy restaurant

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:06.430
I might only bring one bottle
but have a multi-course meal

00:35:06.430 --> 00:35:08.300
with many different flavors.

00:35:08.300 --> 00:35:11.360
Sometimes you can order
the tasting menu's wine

00:35:11.360 --> 00:35:14.990
but they're not usually as high
quality as the restaurant food.

00:35:14.990 --> 00:35:17.880
What would you suggest
to do in this dilemma?

00:35:17.880 --> 00:35:20.970
DANIEL BOULUD: Ah,
well in that case

00:35:20.970 --> 00:35:23.570
you tell them to
skip the pairing

00:35:23.570 --> 00:35:26.170
and order yourself
a nice bottle.

00:35:26.170 --> 00:35:28.400
And usually if you
have four people

00:35:28.400 --> 00:35:31.180
it's easy to have a bottle
of white, bottle of red.

00:35:31.180 --> 00:35:35.890
If you have two people it's
maybe a little too much.

00:35:35.890 --> 00:35:37.300
Yeah, exactly.

00:35:37.300 --> 00:35:42.450
So, to me, I like to try a
very fresh, light pinot noir.

00:35:42.450 --> 00:35:49.590
I mean even American, French,
even it could be Italian also.

00:35:49.590 --> 00:35:51.930
There is some light nebbiolo.

00:35:51.930 --> 00:35:58.010
But I note at
Daniel, for example,

00:35:58.010 --> 00:36:01.610
we purposely choose very
good wine with a pairing

00:36:01.610 --> 00:36:05.380
because, I mean, if we
make all this effort

00:36:05.380 --> 00:36:08.760
making wonderful food and
all that and not giving it

00:36:08.760 --> 00:36:12.660
the level of quality to
the wine, no, absolutely.

00:36:12.660 --> 00:36:16.027
So put pressure on the chef and
say I don't think your pairing

00:36:16.027 --> 00:36:16.610
is good today.

00:36:20.190 --> 00:36:23.660
But there is a new system now.

00:36:23.660 --> 00:36:24.910
I don't know if you have seen.

00:36:24.910 --> 00:36:28.030
It's something you
put on the bottles.

00:36:28.030 --> 00:36:29.800
Yeah, it's fantastic.

00:36:29.800 --> 00:36:33.450
Because now we can open vintage
wine without altering the wine

00:36:33.450 --> 00:36:36.650
and keep it over a week.

00:36:36.650 --> 00:36:39.430
And so now they can
offer a glass of wine.

00:36:39.430 --> 00:36:42.190
So you can have a glass of
white and a glass of red

00:36:42.190 --> 00:36:45.170
of very high-- higher
quality, rather-- than

00:36:45.170 --> 00:36:46.800
have three white and three red.

00:36:46.800 --> 00:36:48.480
It's better to have one glass.

00:36:48.480 --> 00:36:53.210
And follow the path
of the menu with that.

00:36:53.210 --> 00:36:56.140
We are doing it at DB
Bistro right now as a test,

00:36:56.140 --> 00:37:01.230
but at Daniel we
usually open and sell.

00:37:01.230 --> 00:37:04.190
But sometimes in a bistro
where all the average wine

00:37:04.190 --> 00:37:09.050
is between $7 a glass
to maybe $14, when

00:37:09.050 --> 00:37:12.140
you want to sell a
glass at $35 or $50,

00:37:12.140 --> 00:37:15.740
then the risk of selling
the whole bottle that night

00:37:15.740 --> 00:37:17.712
is more challenging.

00:37:17.712 --> 00:37:19.700
AUDIENCE: Yes, my
question is how do you

00:37:19.700 --> 00:37:21.720
get your inspiration?

00:37:21.720 --> 00:37:23.545
Is it your family?

00:37:23.545 --> 00:37:27.210
You say that you wanted to
be a chef when you were 12.

00:37:27.210 --> 00:37:30.270
So what is it your
grandmother, your mother,

00:37:30.270 --> 00:37:32.440
who taught you how to cook?

00:37:32.440 --> 00:37:35.290
Is it your wife now?

00:37:35.290 --> 00:37:36.760
Is it your friends?

00:37:36.760 --> 00:37:39.410
Your friends who are cooks too?

00:37:39.410 --> 00:37:41.020
And clients?

00:37:41.020 --> 00:37:44.045
How do you get all those ideas?

00:37:44.045 --> 00:37:45.170
DANIEL BOULUD: It's Google.

00:37:49.810 --> 00:37:55.390
No, actually traveling
is, of course,

00:37:55.390 --> 00:37:57.210
a big source of inspiration.

00:37:57.210 --> 00:38:00.050
And then when I think
about French cuisine

00:38:00.050 --> 00:38:03.560
and I want to try to continue
to explore French cuisine,

00:38:03.560 --> 00:38:05.650
then I think of home.

00:38:05.650 --> 00:38:07.790
Of course when I think
at home, for example,

00:38:07.790 --> 00:38:10.380
when we make a salad
dressing, I teach Catherine

00:38:10.380 --> 00:38:13.220
how to make my grandmother's
salad dressing where you crush,

00:38:13.220 --> 00:38:16.280
you take a clove of
garlic, you put salt on it,

00:38:16.280 --> 00:38:19.950
you crush it with a fork nicely
until you get a little paste.

00:38:19.950 --> 00:38:22.160
Then you add up a
spoon of mustard,

00:38:22.160 --> 00:38:24.620
and you add a spoon
of vinegar to that.

00:38:24.620 --> 00:38:27.170
And then you pour gently
the olive oil over

00:38:27.170 --> 00:38:28.730
and stir the whole thing.

00:38:28.730 --> 00:38:31.820
And then toss some nice
crisp salad inside this.

00:38:31.820 --> 00:38:33.570
And serve that with a
little fresh fromage

00:38:33.570 --> 00:38:37.460
blanc and some hot
and spring potatoes,

00:38:37.460 --> 00:38:38.742
freshly roasted potatoes.

00:38:38.742 --> 00:38:39.700
I think it's delicious.

00:38:39.700 --> 00:38:41.390
That's my grandmother's cooking.

00:38:41.390 --> 00:38:44.740
I remember we always
made soup also at home.

00:38:44.740 --> 00:38:48.030
Soups are something
every night--

00:38:48.030 --> 00:38:51.010
it don't matter what
it was-- we made soup.

00:38:51.010 --> 00:38:53.240
But then we have
stuff at home too.

00:38:53.240 --> 00:38:58.090
For example, we used to kill
the chicken on Thursday.

00:38:58.090 --> 00:38:59.810
Yeah, on Thursday
we used to kill

00:38:59.810 --> 00:39:02.800
the chicken for
the farmer's market

00:39:02.800 --> 00:39:05.190
and we would keep the
blood of the chicken.

00:39:05.190 --> 00:39:07.380
And on Friday we
would make an omelette

00:39:07.380 --> 00:39:09.730
with the blood of the
chicken, like a blood

00:39:09.730 --> 00:39:11.490
pudding of chicken blood.

00:39:11.490 --> 00:39:15.180
And slice that like an
omelette, flat omelette.

00:39:15.180 --> 00:39:16.590
But it was very nutritious.

00:39:16.590 --> 00:39:18.590
When you are a kid,
you need some iron,

00:39:18.590 --> 00:39:20.850
eat some chicken blood.

00:39:20.850 --> 00:39:22.740
But besides that
there is, of course,

00:39:22.740 --> 00:39:28.390
today traveling
and the young chefs

00:39:28.390 --> 00:39:29.850
traveling with me-- the team.

00:39:29.850 --> 00:39:32.710
The team I have, I think
that's where I get the most

00:39:32.710 --> 00:39:35.960
inspiration because they come
from all over the world, some

00:39:35.960 --> 00:39:38.950
of them, and they
all bring something.

00:39:38.950 --> 00:39:43.450
We sometimes sit down with
them, we discuss ideas.

00:39:43.450 --> 00:39:45.960
I sit down with my
chefs and we always

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:50.330
talk about what else can
we do new, different.

00:39:50.330 --> 00:39:54.450
And I have a good
team of chefs and we

00:39:54.450 --> 00:39:58.550
have a great way of
communicating among each other.

00:39:58.550 --> 00:40:01.240
And I think it's
at the end we want

00:40:01.240 --> 00:40:03.860
to make sure that
the food feels right.

00:40:03.860 --> 00:40:11.080
And the food, it's interesting,
it tastes like food,

00:40:11.080 --> 00:40:17.530
and it really-- for me,
sometimes creativity

00:40:17.530 --> 00:40:20.630
is not always what
I'm thinking first.

00:40:20.630 --> 00:40:23.490
It's more the
composition of the dish.

00:40:23.490 --> 00:40:24.950
I think of the protein.

00:40:24.950 --> 00:40:30.180
I think of what I want to marry
that protein with, if it's

00:40:30.180 --> 00:40:34.280
a fish filet, I want a
particular texture, thickness,

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:36.990
or feel, and how
I want to cook it.

00:40:36.990 --> 00:40:41.150
And then from that now
how I want to season it,

00:40:41.150 --> 00:40:43.950
and what kind of acidity
I want to bring around it,

00:40:43.950 --> 00:40:47.340
and what kind of contrast
and texture, and all that.

00:40:47.340 --> 00:40:49.050
So it's kind of a
gradual buildup.

00:40:49.050 --> 00:40:51.280
And we discuss that with chefs.

00:40:51.280 --> 00:40:56.730
And some of the dishes make
it, sometime in the long run,

00:40:56.730 --> 00:41:01.220
and some dishes disappear and
we go over it and work them out

00:41:01.220 --> 00:41:03.530
again.

00:41:03.530 --> 00:41:04.500
Yeah.

00:41:04.500 --> 00:41:05.850
AUDIENCE: Hi, chef.

00:41:05.850 --> 00:41:07.830
My question is-- I
really loved hearing

00:41:07.830 --> 00:41:10.090
the history of how
you grew up with food,

00:41:10.090 --> 00:41:14.140
and grew up on a farm, and
your time as a line chef

00:41:14.140 --> 00:41:15.290
and then moving up.

00:41:15.290 --> 00:41:17.970
I'm really curious to hear
about how you sort of moved

00:41:17.970 --> 00:41:20.810
from being an individual
chef, being a sous chef,

00:41:20.810 --> 00:41:23.190
and so on, to eventually
opening a restaurant,

00:41:23.190 --> 00:41:25.940
and now, obviously, you
have many restaurants.

00:41:25.940 --> 00:41:29.220
How have you been able to do
that successfully to scale,

00:41:29.220 --> 00:41:30.470
to many different restaurants?

00:41:30.470 --> 00:41:32.680
And what have you learned
from that process?

00:41:32.680 --> 00:41:34.096
DANIEL BOULUD: I
know I think what

00:41:34.096 --> 00:41:39.680
I've learned is to
choose your partner well.

00:41:39.680 --> 00:41:42.100
I was very lucky
when I was looking

00:41:42.100 --> 00:41:43.930
to raise money to open
my first restaurant.

00:41:46.620 --> 00:41:48.900
I was almost 3/4 there.

00:41:48.900 --> 00:41:53.470
I mean I had maybe $1.5 million
and I needed $2.5 million.

00:41:53.470 --> 00:41:59.690
So I sit down with a
gentleman and he told me,

00:41:59.690 --> 00:42:04.990
say, you know, I'd rather be the
one with you than one of them.

00:42:04.990 --> 00:42:07.430
And we'll do much
better business

00:42:07.430 --> 00:42:11.030
together if we are
just the two of us.

00:42:11.030 --> 00:42:15.820
I think that was maybe
the best day in my life

00:42:15.820 --> 00:42:19.430
because then I
found a partner who

00:42:19.430 --> 00:42:23.430
was the CEO of a very large
company in America before

00:42:23.430 --> 00:42:24.540
and he was retiring.

00:42:24.540 --> 00:42:26.070
20 years ago he was retiring.

00:42:26.070 --> 00:42:27.450
Now he is 81.

00:42:27.450 --> 00:42:31.850
And he didn't know what he was
going to do in his retirement,

00:42:31.850 --> 00:42:34.950
and he felt I'm not
risking too much money.

00:42:34.950 --> 00:42:39.090
So I'll help that
little boy there

00:42:39.090 --> 00:42:40.430
with his first restaurant.

00:42:40.430 --> 00:42:42.970
And then from that
he, of course,

00:42:42.970 --> 00:42:45.810
guided me through the business.

00:42:45.810 --> 00:42:48.410
He counted on me to
take care of everything

00:42:48.410 --> 00:42:52.000
and he counted on me to
build my team to do it,

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:55.470
but he was always a good
guiding line for business.

00:42:55.470 --> 00:42:58.550
And I think trust is
the most important thing

00:42:58.550 --> 00:43:01.000
in this business
because when a business

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:06.420
where you could be tempted
to steal from your partner,

00:43:06.420 --> 00:43:09.100
you could be tempted to
steal from your business,

00:43:09.100 --> 00:43:13.950
and so it's the most important
thing, I think, trust.

00:43:13.950 --> 00:43:15.990
And that's why, I
think, 20 years later

00:43:15.990 --> 00:43:18.380
we're still very good partners.

00:43:18.380 --> 00:43:24.290
He's not too young anymore,
but I think the team

00:43:24.290 --> 00:43:26.560
after the team I have
built over the year,

00:43:26.560 --> 00:43:29.260
the CFO today is
with me 20 years.

00:43:29.260 --> 00:43:34.820
The COO is with me 16 years, but
he was already a cook with me

00:43:34.820 --> 00:43:36.210
25 years ago.

00:43:36.210 --> 00:43:39.060
And then in between he went
to Cornell hotel school

00:43:39.060 --> 00:43:42.200
and he did hotel management
and different things.

00:43:42.200 --> 00:43:44.670
And then he came back with
me as director of operations

00:43:44.670 --> 00:43:46.100
and now he's CEO.

00:43:46.100 --> 00:43:54.380
And then director of operations
has been with me for 16 years.

00:43:54.380 --> 00:43:57.880
The chef de cuisine
at Daniel, 17 years.

00:43:57.880 --> 00:44:02.110
The executive chef, 17 years.

00:44:02.110 --> 00:44:03.250
Jean Francois.

00:44:03.250 --> 00:44:04.700
Eddy, 11 years.

00:44:04.700 --> 00:44:09.620
And I have a maitre d' who is in
the book also with his family.

00:44:09.620 --> 00:44:12.005
And now I have the second
generation, his son, also

00:44:12.005 --> 00:44:12.630
as a maitre d'.

00:44:12.630 --> 00:44:14.930
And the two of them,
father and son.

00:44:14.930 --> 00:44:17.410
And you work with me
for 30 years almost.

00:44:20.710 --> 00:44:24.990
But beside that the
average age at Daniel,

00:44:24.990 --> 00:44:29.230
and the average age in the
group is about, I would say, 25,

00:44:29.230 --> 00:44:32.639
26 years old because there's
a lot of young people.

00:44:32.639 --> 00:44:34.930
AUDIENCE: I just want to tell
you, first of all, Daniel

00:44:34.930 --> 00:44:37.490
has not only been the
best dining experience,

00:44:37.490 --> 00:44:39.620
the food is phenomenal,
best I've had in the world,

00:44:39.620 --> 00:44:44.120
but also the dining experience
itself is very, very special.

00:44:44.120 --> 00:44:46.170
But I wanted to ask
you, as much as I'd

00:44:46.170 --> 00:44:48.830
like to eat Daniel cuisine
every day at the level

00:44:48.830 --> 00:44:50.730
that you have it,
what do you eat

00:44:50.730 --> 00:44:53.680
on a regular basis
for a casual day?

00:44:53.680 --> 00:44:55.150
DANIEL BOULUD: Today?

00:44:55.150 --> 00:44:58.110
I had that wonderful vegetable.

00:44:58.110 --> 00:45:01.100
I had a salad,
wonderful vegetables.

00:45:01.100 --> 00:45:05.240
The pan roasted fish
with fennel and raisin,

00:45:05.240 --> 00:45:06.230
a little bit of turkey.

00:45:06.230 --> 00:45:07.860
It was very healthy,
the lunch today.

00:45:07.860 --> 00:45:13.260
And at lunch usually I have a
salad or a soup and one course.

00:45:13.260 --> 00:45:16.100
I don't eat bread
so much anymore.

00:45:16.100 --> 00:45:18.540
I try to be careful
because that's often

00:45:18.540 --> 00:45:20.470
the hardest thing to shed away.

00:45:20.470 --> 00:45:24.430
And I try to eat healthy.

00:45:24.430 --> 00:45:26.770
I drink a little bit of wine.

00:45:26.770 --> 00:45:30.300
I try to control what I do.

00:45:30.300 --> 00:45:32.750
And now Catherine wants
to be a nutritionist.

00:45:32.750 --> 00:45:34.760
She wants to pass a
master in nutrition.

00:45:34.760 --> 00:45:38.730
So very soon she'll tell
me what to eat every day.

00:45:38.730 --> 00:45:41.440
But I am very concerned
about nutrition.

00:45:41.440 --> 00:45:45.720
And I'm very aware
that the food I make

00:45:45.720 --> 00:45:49.710
is always with the
consciousness of healthiness,

00:45:49.710 --> 00:45:57.010
except the iconic dishes
where you get transported

00:45:57.010 --> 00:45:58.640
into another time,
another world.

00:45:58.640 --> 00:46:01.590
And so you don't look
at that that way.

00:46:01.590 --> 00:46:04.340
But the food we do
at Daniel is always

00:46:04.340 --> 00:46:08.980
with healthy components
of preparation.

00:46:08.980 --> 00:46:11.110
And even if we poach
the fish in butter,

00:46:11.110 --> 00:46:13.290
it does not mean we're
going to serve it in butter.

00:46:13.290 --> 00:46:15.580
So the butter enrich
the cuisson of the fish,

00:46:15.580 --> 00:46:21.870
but still don't really
effect the quantity

00:46:21.870 --> 00:46:24.310
of butter going
in the dish also.

00:46:24.310 --> 00:46:26.985
AUDIENCE: With so many different
restaurants now all over

00:46:26.985 --> 00:46:30.240
around the world, and your name
is on, I guess, all of them,

00:46:30.240 --> 00:46:30.740
right?

00:46:30.740 --> 00:46:33.376
So how do you still
manage to spend time

00:46:33.376 --> 00:46:35.750
in some of the restaurants
and keep your influence there?

00:46:35.750 --> 00:46:39.210
And do you find
that there is chefs

00:46:39.210 --> 00:46:42.200
that tend to stay more in
the kitchen versus chefs

00:46:42.200 --> 00:46:42.740
that expand?

00:46:42.740 --> 00:46:44.050
How do you look at that?

00:46:44.050 --> 00:46:47.160
DANIEL BOULUD: Well
we do a Google Hangout

00:46:47.160 --> 00:46:47.990
with all the guys.

00:46:51.870 --> 00:46:53.850
For example, I just came
back from Singapore.

00:46:53.850 --> 00:46:54.450
I did a tour.

00:46:54.450 --> 00:46:56.030
Hong Kong, Beijing, Singapore.

00:46:56.030 --> 00:46:58.410
I have a restaurant in
Beijing and Singapore.

00:46:58.410 --> 00:47:01.690
So I go there.

00:47:01.690 --> 00:47:04.560
I taste new things there.

00:47:04.560 --> 00:47:09.340
We do also special events
and we meet some media

00:47:09.340 --> 00:47:12.050
and have a pow-wow
with the team.

00:47:12.050 --> 00:47:14.260
But I have a
corporate management.

00:47:14.260 --> 00:47:16.620
And the corporate
management-- so either right

00:47:16.620 --> 00:47:19.160
now, our COO in Asia.

00:47:19.160 --> 00:47:20.880
But then after
that following will

00:47:20.880 --> 00:47:23.010
be a director of
operations who might go,

00:47:23.010 --> 00:47:26.140
then maybe my corporate
chef, and I'm going back

00:47:26.140 --> 00:47:29.280
in spring, I think,
or after spring.

00:47:29.280 --> 00:47:31.590
And so I go about
twice a year there.

00:47:31.590 --> 00:47:36.100
But every week we
have a conference call

00:47:36.100 --> 00:47:38.290
via video, and video call.

00:47:38.290 --> 00:47:41.090
And we have the team
there sitting down--

00:47:41.090 --> 00:47:46.360
sommelier, manager, chef,
sous chef, pastry chef, maitre

00:47:46.360 --> 00:47:49.380
d'hotel, and the key
people, management.

00:47:49.380 --> 00:47:51.250
And we have also
the key management

00:47:51.250 --> 00:47:54.030
of the corporate
group in New York.

00:47:54.030 --> 00:47:55.940
And for one hour
they have a meeting

00:47:55.940 --> 00:47:59.510
recapping on what they have
done that week in everything

00:47:59.510 --> 00:48:04.400
in food, in wine, clients,
promotion, training, and all

00:48:04.400 --> 00:48:04.900
that.

00:48:04.900 --> 00:48:10.360
And then they get also some
new information from that,

00:48:10.360 --> 00:48:11.690
from the headquarter.

00:48:11.690 --> 00:48:14.800
But also we designed
a program where

00:48:14.800 --> 00:48:18.860
we have all the menus, all
the recipes, into one program.

00:48:18.860 --> 00:48:21.260
And every chef can
have access to that.

00:48:21.260 --> 00:48:26.380
And so Singapore can inspire
himself from London chef.

00:48:26.380 --> 00:48:28.650
And the chef from
London can look at what

00:48:28.650 --> 00:48:31.590
the one in New York [INAUDIBLE]
what kind of new dish he did.

00:48:31.590 --> 00:48:35.030
So it stays within
the DNA of Daniel.

00:48:35.030 --> 00:48:37.810
And they have the freedom
to be able to also come up

00:48:37.810 --> 00:48:40.150
with ideas themselves.

00:48:40.150 --> 00:48:43.860
That's more or less
the way it works.

00:48:43.860 --> 00:48:47.310
But now it's almost 1,400 people
so it's not as much as Google.

00:48:50.192 --> 00:48:51.150
I think it's different.

00:48:51.150 --> 00:48:55.370
I think the Bay Area-- I
mean you go from, of course,

00:48:55.370 --> 00:49:00.310
north of Napa from Yountville
and even Sonoma to all the way

00:49:00.310 --> 00:49:02.405
down to south of LA.

00:49:02.405 --> 00:49:08.030
I think there is an amazing,
amazing collection of chefs.

00:49:08.030 --> 00:49:12.610
And different styles, some
of them, different ambition.

00:49:12.610 --> 00:49:15.710
Of course, I mean
in New York we have,

00:49:15.710 --> 00:49:20.440
I think, our own style
of restaurants as well.

00:49:20.440 --> 00:49:24.780
Here, I love
restaurants like Saison.

00:49:24.780 --> 00:49:26.490
Last time I went to Benu.

00:49:26.490 --> 00:49:30.400
I went to a state
bird provision.

00:49:30.400 --> 00:49:31.640
It was fantastic.

00:49:31.640 --> 00:49:33.960
I love his cooking also.

00:49:33.960 --> 00:49:35.900
Great, great food.

00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:36.490
Tastes well.

00:49:36.490 --> 00:49:38.010
Fresh.

00:49:38.010 --> 00:49:40.290
Great seasoning.

00:49:40.290 --> 00:49:42.250
Not too esoteric.

00:49:42.250 --> 00:49:46.230
I mean it really
tastes what it is.

00:49:46.230 --> 00:49:50.100
And I think the talent
here is incredible.

00:49:50.100 --> 00:49:55.450
It's incredible but it's a
little bit more free spirited

00:49:55.450 --> 00:49:59.460
than maybe in New York where you
have French, you have Italian.

00:49:59.460 --> 00:50:01.920
But the Italian restaurant I
went to, SPQR, last night--

00:50:01.920 --> 00:50:03.700
it was fantastic also.

00:50:03.700 --> 00:50:04.970
Great, great meal.

00:50:04.970 --> 00:50:10.350
And, of course, I know Queens
also, the restaurant Queens,

00:50:10.350 --> 00:50:11.266
for a long time.

00:50:11.266 --> 00:50:12.390
And then there is La Folie.

00:50:12.390 --> 00:50:16.860
There is Piperade,
the French chef.

00:50:16.860 --> 00:50:18.069
Hubert Keller.

00:50:18.069 --> 00:50:19.110
I love those restaurants.

00:50:19.110 --> 00:50:22.070
But I'm not coming to see
the French because-- I

00:50:22.070 --> 00:50:24.150
may have a drink
with them, but I

00:50:24.150 --> 00:50:26.380
wanted to see what
the other chefs.

00:50:26.380 --> 00:50:29.110
So I would like to go
to Koi and Manresa.

00:50:29.110 --> 00:50:31.080
I missed it because
of the weekend.

00:50:31.080 --> 00:50:33.010
And Menresa, as well,
who is really fantastic.

00:50:36.470 --> 00:50:39.330
But there is a lot happening.

00:50:39.330 --> 00:50:44.450
And what I'm looking forward
is to see the next generation

00:50:44.450 --> 00:50:46.210
who are working now
with those young chefs

00:50:46.210 --> 00:50:48.084
and what they're going
to do themselves next.

00:50:51.720 --> 00:50:56.380
But there's definitely
a concern and a return

00:50:56.380 --> 00:50:58.530
to tradition sometimes.

00:50:58.530 --> 00:51:01.160
Like I see, for
example, at Saison.

00:51:01.160 --> 00:51:03.470
It's doing a very
creative cooking

00:51:03.470 --> 00:51:06.070
but they still have
this wood fire.

00:51:06.070 --> 00:51:08.720
You need the fire
to cook as well,

00:51:08.720 --> 00:51:11.690
to smoke, to flavor,
to cook, and I

00:51:11.690 --> 00:51:15.470
think it's fantastic
to combine the two.

00:51:15.470 --> 00:51:18.960
Thank you very much for
spending time with me here.

